        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "Short answer (no numbers yet): The chelate effect magnitude is expected to vary across Cu2+, Ni2+, and Zn2+ rather than be constant. A reasonable hypothesis is that ligand‑field and structural factors amplify the entropic chelate advantage to different degrees for each metal:\n- Ni2+ (d8) has a sizable octahedral LFSE (≈−1.2Δo), so bidentate chelation by ethylenediamine (en) is enthalpically favored in addition to the entropic gain, predicting a relatively larger ΔlogK.\n- Cu2+ (d9) experiences Jahn–Teller distortion; en coordinates strongly in the equatorial plane, whereas a 1:2 ammine set places one NH3 in weaker axial sites. This can enhance the relative stability of M(en)2+ over M(NH3)2 2+, giving a moderate-to-large ΔlogK.\n- Zn2+ (d10) has essentially zero LFSE; its chelate effect is mostly entropic, so ΔlogK should be smaller than for Ni2+ (and often Cu2+).",
